      'Algorithmic policing': 'Predictive policing is a live essay in every discipline you might transfer into: criminology\'s feedback loops, philosophy\'s preemption problem, history\'s continuity from older surveillance of Black communities, literature\'s dystopias arriving as procurement. The scholarly move is connecting the tool to its lineage; this week supplies the sources.',
      'Digital border technologies': 'The border is a seminar topic made concrete: sovereignty, identity, and classification enacted in code. Biometric borders literalize old questions about who counts as belonging. Your transfer disciplines each hold a piece: political science the policy, anthropology the lived crossing, ethics the justification. The technology is where they meet.',
      'Coded exposure at the border of policing': 'Du Bois wrote about being seen as a problem; Benjamin updates the observation for databases. Coded exposure gives you a bridge concept between canonical texts on surveillance and the present infrastructure. Essays that walk that bridge, from lantern laws to license-plate readers, do this course\'s core intellectual work.',
      'Default discrimination, named by the Supreme Court': 'R. v. Le is a primary source worth close-reading: the Court cites social science on carding to shape the reasonable-person standard. It is evidence that documented experience can rewrite doctrine, a case study in how scholarship becomes law. That pathway, research to recognition, is one your degree can aim at.',
